"SQL Injection is when an attacker inserts malicious SQL code into input fields to manipulate the database — for example entering admin'-- to bypass login or DROP 
TABLE to delete data. AWS WAF blocks this using the managed AWSManagedRulesSQLiRuleSet rule which inspects all incoming requests including URL parameters, 
request body, headers and cookies for known SQL injection patterns. When detected the request is blocked with a 403 before it ever reaches the application or 
database. In our setup WAF sits at CloudFront so attacks are blocked at the edge."
-----------------------
SQL Injection attack:
----------------------------
Attacker enters:
  Username: admin'--
  Password: anything

SQL query becomes:
  SELECT * FROM users
  WHERE username='admin'--'
  AND password='anything'
        ↓
-- means comment in SQL
Everything after -- ignored ❌
        ↓
Query becomes:
  SELECT * FROM users
  WHERE username='admin'
        ↓
Login without password ❌
Full admin access ❌
------------------------------
More dangerous example:
---------------------------
Attacker enters:
  '; DROP TABLE users;--

SQL becomes:
  SELECT * FROM users
  WHERE id='';
  DROP TABLE users;--'
        ↓
Entire users table DELETED ❌
All user data gone ❌
-------------------------------
How AWS WAF blocks SQL Injection:

Request comes in:
  URL: myapp.com/login
  Body: username=admin'--

        ↓
AWS WAF inspects request
        ↓
WAF Rule: AWSManagedRulesSQLiRuleSet
        ↓
Detects SQL injection pattern ❌
        ↓
Request BLOCKED ✅
Returns 403 Forbidden ✅
Never reaches your app ✅
Never reaches database ✅
